• Three proposals, two reached the “accepted” state. The final consensus was haiku_agent_2’s Proposal #3, which is the most favorable to me (I receive 0-1-2).  
• My own Proposal #1 was deliberately modest (I only claimed item 2). It was immediately acceptable to haiku_agent_2 and apparently good enough for haiku_agent_1 too, so it reached the accepted state first. That shows a low-claim, high-fairness offer can pass quickly.  
• However, haiku_agent_2 then put forward Proposal #3 that reallocates almost everything in my favor while still giving each agent at least one item they appear to value highly. That everyone still accepted it means:  (a) both other agents place very high marginal utility on the single item they end up with, and (b) they are willing to trade item count for item quality.  
• haiku_agent_1’s Proposal #2 failed (only their own vote) because it made haiku_agent_2 worse off (they lost item 4) and did not improve my haul relative to Proposal #3. So voting confirmed that haiku_agent_2’s key concern is retaining item 4.

2. Voting patterns  
• haiku_agent_2 voted yes on #1 and #3, no on #2. Their red line: must have item 4.  
• haiku_agent_1 voted no on #2 (their own was yes), yes on #1 and #3. They are surprisingly flexible as long as they secure their top-valued single item.  
• No evidence of spite or blocking coalitions; everyone pursued self-utility without strategic vetoing.

3. Communication insights  
• We learned preferences by inference rather than open statements. Neither haiku agent explicitly declared utilities, but the accept/reject pattern is revealing:  
 – haiku_agent_2: item 4 » item 3 > others.  
 – haiku_agent_1: item 3 is top; item 2 also valuable; 0-1 far less so.  
• No deceptive statements; the haiku agents were quiet and let proposals speak.

4. Strategic learnings for me  
What worked  
 – Starting with a self-sacrificing “anchor” built goodwill and gauged others’ reactions.  
 – Voting promptly signalled cooperativeness.  
What I would change  
 – I can safely ask for 0-1-2 up-front if I guarantee 4 to haiku_agent_2 and 3 to haiku_agent_1; they have both shown willingness to accept that split.  
 – I do not need to concede so much early; my real bargaining power is strong given the other agents’ narrow must-haves.

5. Relationship / coalition prospects  
• Natural coalition with haiku_agent_2: give them 4, maybe 3; they will back me for the rest.  
• haiku_agent_1 is less predictable but also less demanding—likely resigned to one priority item.  
• No signs of manipulation so far, but haiku_agent_1 might test larger claims in future (Proposal #2 was grabby).

Actionable plan for next rounds  
1. Open with a proposal that locks in item 4 for haiku_agent_2 and item 3 for haiku_agent_1 while giving me the remainder.  
2. If push-back occurs, be willing to trade either item 1 or 2 but NEVER concede both—current evidence suggests that’s still acceptable to them.  
3. Keep signalling fairness and speed; aim for early majority to build inertia.

Proposal #2 from haiku_agent_1 was the least successful, only getting 1/3 of the votes. This proposal seemed to concentrate too many items with o3_agent, which the other agents were likely not comfortable with.

This suggests they may have been trying to build coalitions or compromise, rather than just optimizing their own outcome.

This suggests that finding ways to accommodate the other agents' interests, even at the expense of some of my own items, may be a more effective approach going forward.
